question:
When converting an h-parameter matrix to an ABCD-parameter matrix for a two-port network, which of the following expressions correctly represents the ABCD parameter A?

A. A = h_{11} / h_{21}

B. A = (h_{11} h_{22} - h_{12} h_{21}) / h_{21}

C. A = -h_{22} / h_{21}

D. A = (h_{12} h_{21} - h_{11} h_{22}) / h_{21}

output:
The correct choice is B.

Explanation: The reference text states that "the geometry can be varied widely" (i.e., many possible topologies exist) because practical considerations limit achievable values; it then lists several key effects caused by varying geometry:
- Inductance varies with length or area depending on winding density;
- Quality factor decreases when more than one turn per layer exists due to parasitic resistance/inductive coupling among layers;
- Capacitances vary significantly across different configurations—some show large increases while others decrease dramatically;
- Dimensions change substantially from simple shapes like rectangular coils up through helical spirals into very long thin strips;
- Each configuration requires careful analysis and experimentation since no analytic formula applies universally.

These points collectively explain why multiple geometries present complexity: they produce interdependent changes in L, Q, C, physical size, and require empirical tuning rather than relying solely on an idealized model. Therefore option B best captures this reasoning succinctly.
